2
00:00:12,780 --> 00:00:17,860
Major Depressive Disorder can begin at any age, but onset does increase significantly

3
00:00:17,870 --> 00:00:19,260
with puberty.

4
00:00:19,270 --> 00:00:24,620
In Western nations, incidence seems to peak in the 20s although it is not uncommon for

5
00:00:24,620 --> 00:00:26,480
onset to be in later life (Kessler et al., 2003).

6
00:00:26,700 --> 00:00:30,720
Persistent Depressive Disorder tends to have an early and chronic onset.

7
00:00:30,720 --> 00:00:36,030
By definition, of course, Persistent Depressive Disorder is a chronic disorder.

8
00:00:36,030 --> 00:00:40,400
The course of Major Depressive Disorder on the other hand is quite variable.

9
00:00:40,400 --> 00:00:46,170
Some people rarely experience remission – defined as a period of 2 or more months with no symptoms,

10
00:00:46,170 --> 00:00:49,399
or no more than 2 symptoms at a mild level.

11
00:00:49,399 --> 00:00:55,160
Others however can go for a number of years without experiencing a major depressive episode.

12
00:00:55,160 --> 00:00:59,900
Most people, given enough time, will recover without intervention.

13
00:00:59,900 --> 00:01:02,579
This is referred to as spontaneous recovery.

14
00:01:02,579 --> 00:01:08,000
For roughly 2 in 5 people with Major Depressive Disorder, spontaneous recovery will occur

15
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:13,560
within 3 months of onset; and for 4 in 5 people, this will happen within 12 months of onset

16
